{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/run-apache-airflow-on-windows-10-without-docker-3c5754bb98b4", "time": 1683016807.529417, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/run-apache-airflow-on-windows-10-without-docker-3c5754bb98b4/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Run Apache Airflow on Windows 10 without Docker | by Philipp Schmalen | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Run Apache Airflow on Windows 10 without Docker", "description": "Apache Airflow is a great tool to manage and schedule all steps of a data pipeline. However, running it on Windows 10 can be challenging. Airflow\u2019s official Quick Start suggests a smooth start, but\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://airflow.apache.org/docs/stable/start.html", "anchor_text": "Quick Start", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.docker.com/", "anchor_text": "Docker", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.astronomer.io/guides/airflow-wsl/", "anchor_text": "blogs", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/32378494/how-to-run-airflow-on-windows", "anchor_text": "Stack Overflow", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://dev.to/jfhbrook/how-to-run-airflow-on-windows-with-docker-2d01", "anchor_text": "see this tutorial", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://github.com/philippschmalen/etl_spark_airflow_emr", "anchor_text": "on Github", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "https://drivendata.github.io/cookiecutter-data-science/", "anchor_text": "Cookiecutter data science", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://github.com/philippschmalen/etl_spark_airflow_emr", "anchor_text": "this repository", "paragraph_index": 21}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/philippschmalen/", "anchor_text": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/philippschmalen/", "paragraph_index": 23}], "all_paragraphs": ["Apache Airflow is a great tool to manage and schedule all steps of a data pipeline. However, running it on Windows 10 can be challenging. Airflow\u2019s official Quick Start suggests a smooth start, but solely for Linux users. What about us Windows 10 people if we want to avoid Docker? These steps worked for me and hopefully will work for you, too.", "After struggling with incorrect configuration, I eventually found a way to install and launch my first Airflow instance. I am happy to share my insights and list the steps that worked for me. If this also works for you \u2014 the better!", "How to install and run Airflow locally with Windows subsystem for Linux (WSL) with these steps:", "5. Install Airflow: pip3 install apache-airflow", "6. Run sudo nano /etc/wsl.conf, insert the block below, save and exit with ctrl+s ctrl+x", "7. Run nano ~/.bashrc, insert the line below, save and exit with ctrl+s ctrl+x", "8. Run airflow info, inspect errors and install missing packages with pip3 install [package-name], restart terminal, try airflow info again", "I managed to make it work with a Windows subsystem for Linux (WSL) which was recommended on blogs or Stack Overflow. However, even these resources lead into dead ends.", "After a lot of try and error I want to help you with an approach that worked for me. Try to follow these steps. If you get stuck, try to resolve the error by installing missing dependencies, restart terminal or carefully check the instructions.", "Run the following commands run in terminal:", "3. Install Airflow: pip3 install apache-airflow", "5. To access directories like /c/users/philipp instead of /mnt/c/users/philipp insert the code block, save and exit with ctrl+s ctrl+x", "6. Type nano ~/.bashrc and define the environment variable AIRFLOW_HOME by adding the code below, then save and exit with ctrl+s, ctrl+x", "7. Close terminal, open cmd and wsl shell again (type wsl)", "8. Install missing packages with pip3 install [package-name]", "9. Restart terminal, activate wsl, run airflow info", "Docker offers a controlled environment (container) to run applications. Since Airflow solely runs on Linux it is a great candidate to use a Docker container. However, Docker is sometimes hard to debug, clunky and could add another layer of confusion. If you want to run Airflow with Docker see this tutorial.", "Now it is time to have a look at Airflow! Is AIRFLOW_HOME where you expect it to be? Open two cmd windows, activate wsl and run:", "Unfortunately, WSL does not support background tasks ( daemon). This is why we have to open one terminal for airflow webserver and one for airflow scheduler.", "Copying your DAGs back and forth from a project folder to Airflow home directory is cumbersome. Fortunately, we can automate this with a bash script. For example, my project root directory is in /c/users/philipp/projects/project_name/ and contains one folder with all scripts related to data collection and processing named ./src/data/. I also have one folder for all Airflow-related files in ./src/airflow/. In this folder Have a look at my project Run Spark EMR clusters with Airflow on Github to see the project structure. You find the script deploy.sh in ./src/airflow.", "I am thankful for Cookiecutter data science for inspiration about the project structure.", "This guide outlines the steps for installing Airflow on Windows 10. We use windows subsystem for Linux (WSL) to make it work and avoid Docker, which might be too bulky. Furthermore, I list the commands to check for Airflow\u2019s home directory and start the scheduler and webserver. Lastly, I recommend a project structure, where Airflow\u2019s home path differs from your project path like in this repository. This minimizes further need to configure Airflow and makes it generally accessible for other projects.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data scientist with a background in economics and aviation. Gather evidence \u21c6 make decisions. https://www.linkedin.com/in/philippschmalen/"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F3c5754bb98b4&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppB